# kt — x86-64 Systems Language Compiler (Milestone 1: Hello World ELF)

## Context

We're building "kt", a new systems programming language targeting x86-64 with direct codegen, written in C. The compiler links against musl libc (at `musl/`, v1.2.5) for fully static binaries. The first milestone is compiling `fn main() { puts("Hello, world!") }` into a running ELF binary.

## Project Structure

```
kt/
  musl/                     # musl libc (existing, v1.2.5)
  build/                    # all build artifacts
    musl/                   # musl install prefix
  src/                      # kt compiler (C)
    main.c                  # driver: CLI args, read file, run pipeline
    token.h                 # TokenKind enum, Token struct, SrcLoc
    lexer.h / lexer.c       # tokenizer
    ast.h / ast.c           # AST node types + constructors
    parser.h / parser.c     # recursive descent parser
    codegen.h / codegen.c   # x86-64 GAS assembly emitter
    microparse.h / microparse.c  # @microparse: inline code gen via Claude API + .gen caching
    error.h / error.c       # error reporting (file:line:col format)
    arena.h / arena.c       # bump allocator for AST nodes/strings
  tests/
    hello.kt                # fn main() { puts("Hello, world!") }
  Makefile                  # builds musl, ktc, and runs tests
  .gitignore
```

## Implementation Steps

### Step 1: Build infrastructure
- Write `Makefile` with three targets:
  - `musl`: `cd musl && ./configure --prefix=$(CURDIR)/build/musl --disable-shared && make -j && make install`
  - `ktc`: compile all `src/*.c` with `gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -g -O2 -o build/ktc`
  - `test`: run ktc on hello.kt -> assemble -> link -> execute
- Write `.gitignore` (build/, *.o, *.s)
- Run `make musl` to produce `build/musl/lib/{crt1.o,crti.o,crtn.o,libc.a}`

### Step 2: Manual assembly smoke test
- Hand-write assembly that calls `puts("Hello, world!")` and returns 0
- Assemble with `as --64` and link with `ld -static` against musl CRT + libc.a
- Verify the binary runs -- this validates the link strategy before writing any compiler code

Link command:
```
ld -static -o build/hello \
  build/musl/lib/crt1.o build/musl/lib/crti.o \
  build/hello.o \
  --start-group build/musl/lib/libc.a --end-group \
  build/musl/lib/crtn.o
```

### Step 3: Arena allocator (`arena.h`, `arena.c`)
- Bump allocator backed by `mmap(MAP_ANONYMOUS)`, 1 MB initial size
- `arena_alloc(arena, size, align)` and `arena_free(arena)` (frees everything)

### Step 4: Error module (`error.h`, `error.c`)
- `error_at(SrcLoc, fmt, ...)` -- prints `file:line:col: error: msg` and exits
- `warn_at(SrcLoc, fmt, ...)` -- prints warning, continues

### Step 5: Lexer (`token.h`, `lexer.h`, `lexer.c`)
- Tokens: `FN`, `IDENT`, `STRING`, `INT`, `LPAREN`, `RPAREN`, `LBRACE`, `RBRACE`, `COMMA`, `COLON`, `AT`, `EOF`
- `AT` token (`@`) enables annotation parsing for `@microparse`
- Keyword recognition: scan identifier, check if it matches `"fn"` -> emit `TOK_FN`
- String literals with basic escape sequences (`\n`, `\\`, `\"`)

### Step 6: AST + Parser (`ast.h`, `ast.c`, `parser.h`, `parser.c`)
- Node kinds: `PROGRAM`, `FN_DEF`, `BLOCK`, `EXPR_STMT`, `CALL`, `STRING_LIT`, `INT_LIT`, `IDENT`, `ANNOTATION`
- Each node has a `SrcLoc` for error reporting
- `NODE_ANNOTATION` stores: name (e.g. "microparse"), prompt string, and the AST node it annotates
- Recursive descent parser for this grammar:
  ```
  program    = (annotation? fn_def)*
  annotation = "@" IDENT "(" STRING ")"
  fn_def     = "fn" IDENT "(" ")" block
  block      = "{" stmt* "}"
  stmt       = expr_stmt
  expr_stmt  = expr
  expr       = call_expr | STRING | INT | IDENT
  call_expr  = IDENT "(" args? ")"
  args       = expr ("," expr)*
  ```

### Step 7: Codegen (`codegen.h`, `codegen.c`)
- Emits GAS x86-64 assembly
- String literals collected during codegen, emitted in `.rodata` at end
- Function codegen: `.globl main` / `pushq %rbp` / `movq %rsp, %rbp` / body / `xorl %eax, %eax` / `popq %rbp` / `ret`
- Function calls: load args into `%rdi`, `%rsi`, `%rdx`, `%rcx`, `%r8`, `%r9` per System V ABI, then `call symbol`
- String args: `leaq .LC0(%rip), %rdi` (RIP-relative)

Expected output for hello.kt:
```asm
    .text
    .globl main
    .type main, @function
main:
    pushq   %rbp
    movq    %rsp, %rbp
    leaq    .LC0(%rip), %rdi
    call    puts
    xorl    %eax, %eax
    popq    %rbp
    ret

    .section .rodata
.LC0:
    .string "Hello, world!"
```

### Step 8: Driver (`main.c`) + end-to-end test
- `ktc <input.kt> -o <output.s>`: read file, lex, parse, codegen, write .s
- `make test` runs the full pipeline and executes the binary
- Expected: prints "Hello, world!" and exits 0

### Step 9: @microparse -- AI-powered inline code generation (`microparse.h`, `microparse.c`)

A built-in compiler annotation that calls Claude API to generate kt code inline. The generated code replaces the annotation in the AST and gets compiled into the binary.

Syntax examples:
```kt
@microparse("handle positive, zero, and negative cases")
fn classify(x: i32) -> str { }

@microparse("write a switch for HTTP status codes 200, 404, 500")
fn status_message(code: i32) -> str { }
```

Compiler pipeline integration (between parse and codegen):
```
source.kt -> Lexer -> Parser -> AST
                                  |
                          microparse pass  <--  Claude API
                                  |
                          AST (with generated code spliced in)
                                  |
                               Codegen -> .s file
```

How it works:
1. Parse: `@microparse("prompt")` before a fn with empty body -> `NODE_ANNOTATION` wrapping `NODE_FN_DEF`
2. Cache check: hash(prompt + signature), look for `<source>.gen` file
3. API call (cache miss): send prompt + signature to Claude, get kt source back
4. Splice: re-lex/parse response, replace empty body in AST
5. Cache write: save to `<source>.gen`
6. Codegen: proceeds normally

Caching:
- `.kt.gen` files store generated code + hash
- `--microparse-refresh` forces re-generation
- `--skip-microparse` uses cache only
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` env var required

## Key musl files (reference)
- `musl/arch/x86_64/crt_arch.h` -- `_start` assembly entry point
- `musl/crt/crt1.c` -- `_start_c` calls `__libc_start_main(main, argc, argv, ...)`
- `musl/arch/x86_64/syscall_arch.h` -- syscall register conventions

## Verification
1. `make musl` -- builds musl, produces lib/libc.a and CRT objects
2. `make ktc` -- builds the compiler with no warnings
3. `make test` -- compiles hello.kt -> hello.s -> hello.o -> hello binary, runs it
4. `./build/hello` prints "Hello, world!" and `echo $?` returns 0
5. Write a test `.kt` file with `@microparse` annotation and empty function body
6. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=... ./build/ktc tests/microparse_test.kt -o build/mp_test.s` -- calls Claude, generates body, compiles
7. Verify `.kt.gen` cache file is created; re-running skips the API call
